<TITLE> S Africa's Mboweni warns on inflation: report </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 JOHANNESBURG, April 25 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - South African economic conditions have changed drastically since the last monetary policy committee meeting earlier this month, Reserve Bank Governor Tito Mboweni was quoted as saying on Friday. According to public broadcaster SABC's website, Mboweni complained in an interview about administered prices continuing to rise above the 3 to 6 percent target. It reported that the monetary policy committee, which decides on interest rate movement every two months, may call an emergency meeting in the face of the worsening inflation outlook. South Africa's CPIX inflation rate jumped to 10.1 percent year-on-year in March, its highest level in more than 5 years, raising speculation of another rate increase at the bank's June policy meeting. This followed the latest 50 basis point increase in the repo rate to 11.5 percent on April 10, taking total increases since June 2006 to 450 basis point
